## More complex models (is this a causal graph?)

VanderWeele writes this: 


::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Multivariate reality gives rise to the indicators, from which we draw our measure.r](caual_measurement_graphs_files/figure-html/fig-dag-multivariate-reality-1.png){#fig-dag-multivariate-reality width=100%}
:::
:::



Rather, I would prefer to say A$ = f(X_1, \dots X_n)$, and to make the point we write: 



::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Multivariate reality gives rise to the indicators, from which we draw our measure.r](caual_measurement_graphs_files/figure-html/fig-dag-multivariate-reality-bulbulia-1.png){#fig-dag-multivariate-reality-bulbulia width=100%}
:::
:::








## VanderWeele's model of reality (is this a causal diagramme?)



::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Multivariate reality gives rise to the latent variables,...](caual_measurement_graphs_files/figure-html/fig-dag-multivariate-reality-complete-1.png){#fig-dag-multivariate-reality-complete width=100%}
:::
:::



However this is not a causal graph. Can we do better? 

